There is new information posted on the school district website (https://www.isd2835.org/), then select "JWP School District 2020-21 School Year Information."

The following information is posted on the website:

1. Learning Model Weekly Update - September 3, 2020.

This update highlights a change in the Learning Model for students in grades 7-12 based on newly released county data. Students in grades PreK-6 will be in the Hybrid Model (everyday in-person) and students in grades 7-12 will now be in Distance Learning to start the school year.

2. Parent Handout - Quick Reference Guide

3. Screening & Attendance Information

4. MN Department of Health Decision Tree

5. Screening Video (this will be posted later today)

We understand this change to Distance Learning for students in grades 7-12 will impact families. We are committed to bringing back students in grades 7-12 as soon as safely possible. There will be more information communicated on material pick-up and food service.

Now posted on the JWP School District website (https://www.isd2835.org/) under “”JWP School District 2020-21 School Year Information” is the following information:

Safe Learning Plan - This document contains information on health, safety, procedures, learning models, operations, community education and other areas.

post_text:
When schools closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, hundreds of thousands of Minnesota’s students lost access to school breakfast and lunch. For students who receive free & reduced price school meals, this has been a big gap in their access to food.

The USDA recently approved the state of Minnesota’s application for Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) to help families replace the meals their children lost because schools are closed.

Application deadline for families is July 31, 2020.

https://www.hungersolutions.org/2020/06/05/p-ebt-available-to-help-feed-kids/

The Janesville-Waldorf-Pemberton School staff is preparing for the 2020-2021 school year. The school district is committed to safely bring backing as many students as possible to start the school year. Superintendent Kurt Stumpf will be hosting three online sessions to share more details, answer questions and receive feedback regarding the Return to School plan.

Hi everyone! Mike Berding, Director of Technology and Integration, here.

JWP is pleased to announce the newly reformed JWP website!

This can be found at www.isd2835.org!

Each school has it's own domain now, with calendars, events, images, and notification options.

JWP Elementary : https://elem.isd2835.org
JWP High School: https://hs.isd2835.org
JWP Community Education: https://ce.isd2835.org

The previous site will be up for the remainder of this week as I work to ensure that all necessary content is migrated as well as working on some areas that are under a final reconstruction.

Following this week, though, jwp.k12.mn.us will point to the new website.

We're always looking to better our communications, and the website is included in this. So please, feel free to share your feedback and/or questions with Mike Berding at technology@isd2835.org.

Thanks and have a wonderful week!

post_text:
Congratulations to Mandy Gruis & Kobe Weimert as they received the Richard Krautbauer and Jack Dahl Awards! Both of these awards honor JWP senior student-athletes who show desire on and off the field of play. The recipients of these awards show a good balance of our Core Values: Discipline, Attitude, We over Me, and Grit.

Over her high school career, Mandy participated in volleyball, basketball, softball, musical, and swing show. She plans to attend Minnesota State University, Mankato to major in Nursing.

Kobe participated in football, basketball, baseball, musical, and swing show during his high school career. In the fall he will be attending Central Lakes College to major in Heavy Equipment Operation & Maintenance.

Congratulations to both of our student-athletes!

post_text:
JWP Students & Families,

One item of change this past year has been ALICE training throughout our PreK-12 building. This system of response centers around what ALICE calls our most valuable “assets”- the people in our building.

This year, Officer Johnson and our administrative team has been pivotal in offering scenarios and training for all students and staff. These have been completed during morning meetings, grade level assemblies, and advisory.

In lieu of our ability to conduct our last scenario in the classroom, we are providing all families with Scenario #4, with School Resource Officer Johnson narrating. Please view the presentation and discuss the points found in the slides at home with your child: youtu.be/t_YZgfKdlnU

If you want more information on ALICE, please see their website, or email Officer Johnson at the school.

Steve Johnson, School Resource Officer
sjohnson@isd2835.org
(507) 231-7722

Thank you,

Grant Hanson, Principal
Jeremy Erler, Principal
Steve Johnson, School Resource Officer
Kurt Stumpf, Superintendent

JWP Families,
Since Distance Learning will continue until the end of the school year, we are planning to clean out student lockers and desks this week. The school will be open for students to pick up personal possessions, medications from the health office, and/or return library books on Thursday, April 30. 5 pm – 8 pm N – Z
Please come when able if your scheduled time does NOT work for you.

One ADULT per student (elementary- We are encouraging no children if at all possible)

post_text:
Jordan Schrom, a 2015 JWP graduate, is currently at Hackensack University Medical Center working in the COVID ICU. Last month he received a call to be a nurse out in New Jersey for the next two months. Hackensack University Medical Center is located 15 miles from New York City in one of the hardest hit parts of the country during this pandemic. He is working 48+ hours per week. All hospitals and employees have shifted into disaster mode and are working tirelessly with the affected population. He says that everyone has been so welcoming and very nice to him.

We thank Jordan and all health care workers for helping to keep us safe during this devastating time!

If you would like, leave any words of encouragement for Jordan and all health care workers on this post.

post_text:
JWP Community,
As COVID-19 continues to affect our region, we want to reassure you that the health and safety of our students and staff is our top priority. We have no known cases of COVID-19 among students or staff at Janesville-Waldorf-Pemberton School District. The Minnesota Department of Public Health and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) continue to stress common-sense illness prevention strategies such as staying home when sick, covering your cough and sneezes, and frequent hand washing.
We are following routine cleaning of all frequently touched surfaces in the workplace. We use the cleaning agents that are usually used in these areas and follow the directions on the label.
The District is committed to regular communications with parents and the community through this situation. The District has a Web page dedicated to COVID-19 information (https://sites.google.com/isd2835.org/covid-19/home). The District will provide timely information on that site, as well as any updates via email, social media, and phone as needed.

post_text:
Last week Alex Kleve placed 10th overall at a Regional Spelling Bee, a qualifier for the Scripps National Spelling Bee. He was eliminated with the word 'bursary.' Ms. Gostomczik, long time JWP English teacher, has informed us that in all her years of running the spelling bee, JWP has never had a top ten regional finisher until now!

Alex was in great spirits after the bee and says he wants to give it another try next year! Congratulations Alex!!

Also, thank you Mr. Ermory for running our local Spelling Bee and giving Alex this opportunity!

post_text:
Strategic Planning
The Janesville-Waldorf-Pemberton School Board is looking to update our Strategic Plan this school year. The school district has contracted the services of Bruce Miles from Big River Group, LLC to lead the planning process. JWP Teachers have started to research and set goals for specific Student Success Measures that are mandated by the state as part of the Strategic Plan.

The next step in the Strategic Plan process is to survey all stakeholders to gather input that will guide input sessions. Linked below is a two-question survey that we are asking all JWP community members to complete by Friday, March 13, 2020 at 5:00 p.m.

Community Survey - Strategic Plan
http://survey.constantcontact.com/survey/a07egwbrewtk67b5ymn/start

National School Counseling Week 2019 is Feb. 3–7. The week, sponsored by the American School Counselor Association (ASCA), highlights the unique contribution of school counselors within U.S. school systems and the tremendous impact they can have in helping students achieve school success and plan for a career.

This week, we thank Mrs. Anna Braam for all the work she does to help our JWP students succeed! We couldn't do it without you, Mrs. Braam!
